body:
If so, which versions are currently supported? Which versions are planned to be supported?

If not, can I be added as a maintainer? I understand this project depends on a dead dependency, and would be happy to have a go at reworking it to work without that.

comment_data.body: Why not start by forking it ? You can do a pull request or be added as maintainer later I think.

I believe the project is dead, mostly because of lack of maintainers. Andrewrk is pretty busy, and this project has been nothing but a headache to update ever since 1.7.

Only @andrewrk can add new maintainers to the github and npm, I believe. While we wait for him, however, I'm already registered as a collaborator on both the github and npm, so please fork the project, update it, and create pull-requests. I can verify they work, accept them, and publish new versions to npm.

mineflayer doesn't depend on a dead dependency, it depends on a dead software used to generate the objects, for instance in biome.js. The dependency is [Burger](https://github.com/mcdevs/Burger/tree/master) and [Hamburgular](https://github.com/sadimusi/Hamburglar). The biggest dependency of mineflayer, node-minecraft-protocol is still maintained (although it might be not up-to-date. I'll take a look and update it if it's not the case). 

Thanks for reviving interest in this project btw, and good luck to you if you decide to fork and update it ^^. If you have any questions, I'm on IRC, irc.freenode.net, #mcdevs
@thiecec Yeah if you demonstrate that you know what you're doing via 1 or 2 pull requests I'd be happy to add you as a maintainer.
Node-minecraft-protocol is updated to 1.8, so now all that remains is updating burger OR updating all the block, item, biome, etc definitions by hand.
There's a lot more to do than that. I think basically the entire module needs to be rewritten at this point, or at least re-evaluated. I've abandoned this project indefinitely.

I think its somewhat salvageable, there's a lot of good code in mineflayer still applicable. Started updating Burger https://github.com/mcdevs/Burger/pull/12 but still a ways to go, it may be better to find another means to extract the block and item data (a runtime plugin to iterate Blocks and Items? may be easier than trudging through bytecode)

@andrewrk I've seen quite a lot of work in updating this project to 1.8, and it's pretty successful (we're close to having the digger example working). Mineflayer's API is actually high-enough level that we can easily implement the changes without breaking much. 

@deathcap a forge or bukkit plugin would be a great way to deal with this, now that you mention it. Much easier than dealing with the bytecode :P
@roblabla great, I hope it works out :-)
@andrewrk @rom1504 should be getting commit access to mineflayer. He's a major contributor to mineflayer right now, and has been contributing a great deal of time patching it up for 1.8.
So this project is now maintained again, sometime soon we'll have a 1.1.0 release on npm.
